<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/tbl2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="tblfn3">
<sup>*</sup><p class="display-inline">The values are expressed as the mean and the standard deviation. Toe and linear values represent the rotational stiffness in the toe and linear regions of the torque-angle curve after a bilinear fit. CI = continuous immobilization, PM1 = passive motion protocol 1, and PM2 = passive motion protocol 2.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="tblfn4">
<sup>†</sup><p class="display-inline">Significant (p &lt; 0.017) compared with continuous immobilization.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="tblfn5">
<sup>‡</sup><p class="display-inline">Significant (p &lt; 0.017) compared with passive motion protocol 2.</p>
</div>
</div></section><p>After four weeks of remobilization by means of treadmill running, there were still significant differences in range of motion and joint stiffness. Total range of motion continued to be significantly lower in the passive motion groups as compared with the continuous immobilization group (<a href="#fig5" class="usa-link">Fig. 5</a>) (see <a href="#app1" class="usa-link">Appendix</a>). Again, range of motion was significantly decreased in the internal direction and not the external direction (<a href="#tbl1" class="usa-link">Table I</a>) (see <a href="#app1" class="usa-link">Appendix</a>). At this time point, the only significant joint stiffness increase was seen in terms of internal linear stiffness when passive motion protocol 1 was compared with passive motion protocol 2 and continuous immobilization (<a href="#tbl2" class="usa-link">Table II</a>).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="fig5"><h3 class="obj_head">Fig. 5.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=2752319_JOBOJOS91102421fig5.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/0fbb/2752319/f3f8e7219d44/JOBOJOS91102421fig5.jpg" loading="lazy" height="299" width="408" alt="Fig. 5"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/fig5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>After four weeks of remobilization, range of motion was still significantly decreased with both passive motion protocols. CI = continuous immobilization, PM1 = passive motion protocol 1, and PM2 = passive motion protocol 2. *Significant (p &lt; 0.017) compared with continuous immobilization. Error bars represent the standard deviation.</p></figcaption></figure><p>There was no difference in collagen organization between the group treated with continuous immobilization and the group treated with passive motion protocol 2. In both groups, regardless of postoperative treatment, collagen was still highly disorganized six weeks after surgery, as indicated by the high angular deviation values (<a href="#tbl3" class="usa-link">Table III</a>).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="tbl3"><h3 class="obj_head">TABLE III.</h3>
